We evaluated three different k8s setups:
- MicroK8s HA cluster with Wireguard
- K3s HA cluster with Wireguard
- Standalone K3s clusters connected via Karmada

- K3s shows faster and more stable networking overall compared to MicroK8s

@staticmethod
async def optimal_scale_up_server(chute: Chute) -> Optional[Server]:
    """
    Find the optimal server for scaling up a chute deployment.
    """
    # hostname - chute id
    SERVER_RESTRICTIONS = {
        "gpu-server-05": ["chute-efg"],
    }
    # gpu-short-ref - chute id
    GPU_MODEL_RESTRICTIONS = {
        "a100": ["chute-abc", "chute-def"],
        "h100": ["chute-xyz"],
    }
    
    if chute.ban_reason:
        logger.warning(f"Will not scale up banned chute {chute.chute_id=}: {chute.ban_reason=}")
        return None
        
    supported_gpus = list(chute.supported_gpus)
    if "h200" in supported_gpus and set(supported_gpus) - set(["h200"]):
        supported_gpus = list(set(supported_gpus) - set(["h200"]))
        
    # Filter supported GPUs based on restrictions
    restricted_gpus = []
    for gpu_model, allowed_chutes in GPU_MODEL_RESTRICTIONS.items():
        if gpu_model in supported_gpus and chute.chute_id not in allowed_chutes:
            restricted_gpus.append(gpu_model)
    
    # Remove restricted GPU models from supported_gpus
    supported_gpus = [gpu for gpu in supported_gpus if gpu not in restricted_gpus]
    
    if not supported_gpus:
        logger.warning(f"No supported GPUs available for chute {chute.chute_id=} after applying restrictions")
        return None
        
    total_gpus_per_server = (
        select(Server.server_id, func.count(GPU.gpu_id).label("total_gpus"))
        .select_from(Server)
        .join(GPU, Server.server_id == GPU.server_id)
        .where(GPU.model_short_ref.in_(supported_gpus), GPU.verified.is_(True))
        .group_by(Server.server_id)
        .subquery()
    )
    
    used_gpus_per_server = (
        select(Server.server_id, func.count(GPU.gpu_id).label("used_gpus"))
        .select_from(Server)
        .join(GPU, Server.server_id == GPU.server_id)
        .where(GPU.verified.is_(True), GPU.deployment_id.isnot(None))
        .group_by(Server.server_id)
        .subquery()
    )
    
    query = (
        select(
            Server,
            total_gpus_per_server.c.total_gpus,
            func.coalesce(used_gpus_per_server.c.used_gpus, 0).label("used_gpus"),
            (
                total_gpus_per_server.c.total_gpus
                - func.coalesce(used_gpus_per_server.c.used_gpus, 0)
            ).label("free_gpus"),
        )
        .select_from(Server)
        .join(total_gpus_per_server, Server.server_id == total_gpus_per_server.c.server_id)
        .outerjoin(used_gpus_per_server, Server.server_id == used_gpus_per_server.c.server_id)
        .join(GPU, Server.server_id == GPU.server_id)
        .where(
            GPU.model_short_ref.in_(supported_gpus),
            GPU.verified.is_(True),
            (
                total_gpus_per_server.c.total_gpus
                - func.coalesce(used_gpus_per_server.c.used_gpus, 0)
                >= chute.gpu_count
            ),
            Server.locked.is_(False),
            or_(
                not_(Server.name.in_(list(SERVER_RESTRICTIONS.keys()))),
                and_(
                    Server.name.in_([
                        name for name, allowed_chutes in SERVER_RESTRICTIONS.items()
                        if chute.chute_id in allowed_chutes
                    ])
                )
            )
        )
        .order_by(Server.hourly_cost.asc(), text("free_gpus ASC"))
        .limit(1)
    )
    
    async with get_session() as session:
        result = await session.execute(query)
        row = result.first()
        return row.Server if row else None
```

Nearly done with async jobs, i.e. tasks that take longer than a single API call could do. Originally the idea was for things like video generation of arbitrary length, templated fine tunes, etc.

These async tasks are truly arbitrary, so things like server rental are really no different, just spin up a chute and the "complete" trigger would just be that the user deleted it.

So, when we support 12 concurrent requests per deepseek instance for example and we have an average of 3 requests per instance, we could pre-empt 50% of those instances for rentals without failing requests (and leaving a buffer).

The miners would choose to accept an async job or not, first come first serve response, and they'd ideally get the same compute units for that duration as the top N percentile of nodes of that type running other/classic chutes.

We'd have a dynamic set of preemptible nodes based on utilization metrics in the recent past, ensuring of course miners aren't just boosting one chute artificially before hand to get a high rental score and so on.

Then our underutilized nodes can be used for other things.

Yes it will be tricky to handle, and each job can define timeouts and success criteria, user reports are already a mechanism for feedback, etc.

Also the GPU validation will need to complete and post back extremely fast, i.e. in the expected FLOPS performance for that GPU type, before it can be accepted, and we can do things like monitor VRAM and GPU tensor core utilization during the process and constantly report back, etc.
The good news is the reports (when verified) retroactively negate scores so anyone playing games won't actually benefit, in time.

It goes hand in hand with the other roadmap item of adding baked in verification mechanisms to chutes so the app/chute creator can define validation mechanisms themselves.  For example, video generation can expect N frames in T seconds, and you can check similarity of frame F against the input image or use video embedding model to check similarity to prompt if it's text only, etc.

It's per chute, because the "node selector" can include any number of GPUs.  So basically, we calculate the cheapest GPUs that are capable of running the chute for the specified node selector, then compute units are that price / most expensive GPU * number of gpus required * seconds run (normalized by median miner performance).

So for example, if the chute supports 4090s (and everything up to h200s), you can run it on any of those GPUs but the compute units are based on the cheapest (4090s).

The score also includes invocation count, which is not adjusted by GPU type or anything, just number of completed requests.
